ragm at the level of the \u003Cstrong\u003ET10\u003C/strong\u003E vertebra. This anatomical landmark is important for understanding the relationship between the oesophagus and surrounding structures. \u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E is too high, located in the cervical region. \u003Cstrong\u003ET9\u003C/strong\u003E is slightly above the actual level and \u003Cstrong\u003ET11\u003C/strong\u003E is slightly below the correct level. \u003Cstrong\u003EL1\u003C/strong\u003E is much too low, being in the lumbar region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oesophagus passes through the oesophageal hiatus of the diaphragm at the level of the 10th thoracic vertebra (T10)."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Bains KNS, Kashyap S, Lappin SL. Anatomy, Thorax, Diaphragm. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519558/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42722"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14390"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42722"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T18:06:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T18:06:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7085"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"